\begin{columns}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
  \column{0.6}
  \block{Is the thermal response of local ecosystems a simple up-scaling of species-level (intra-specific) thermal performance curves (TPCs)?}{

    \begin{minipage}[]{0.5\linewidth}
      \makebox[\textwidth][c]{\includegraphics[trim=5cm 0.2cm 5cm 5cm,clip,width=22cm]{EcoModelFigure.pdf}}
  \end{minipage}
  \hspace{.8cm}
  \begin{minipage}[]{0.33\linewidth}
    
    
    {\bf Scaling up} is a linear mapping (strictly what geometric scaling means) between the lower-level phenomenon (here,individual-level or intra-specific thermal responses) and the emergent one of ecosystem functioning. \\

    \begin{equation}
      F \propto \sum_{n}F_{n}
        \end{equation}

    
      \textit{ where {\bf F} is the ecosystem metabolic rate arising from the metabolic rates of {\bf n} individuals}

  \end{minipage}

}
 
  \column{0.4}
  \block{Data \& Theory}{
    \normalsize
    To investigate the mapping between individual and ecosystem metabolism we combine new theory and data on the temperature dependence of key metabolic traits (photosynthesis and respiration rates) at both:
\begin{itemize} \itemsep15pt 
\item Species level: where we use the thermal dependance of more than 300 different species of terrestrial plants (\textit {Biotraits Database})
\item Ecosystem level: using a global data on metabolic fluxes of 118 local terrestrial ecosystems across the world (\textit{Fluxnet Database})
  \end {itemize}
  
  We've performed a preliminary analysis of the data, to get at patterns necessary for parameterizing the model, and also validating it.


    \begin{equation}
	F = F_0\sum_{i=1}^{k} n_i m_i f(m_i)g(T,\theta_i^{1,2,...j})	
    \end{equation}

    \begin{equation}
		F = F_{0} \sum_{i=1}^{k} {x_i \left(f_{P}(m_i) g_P(T) - f_{R}(m_i) g_R(T)\right)}
    \end{equation}

    \begin{equation}
	f_{P}(m_i) g_P(T) = P_{0,i} m_i^{a_P} e^{\frac{-E_{P,i}}{kT}} h(T_{pk_{P,i}}, E_{D_{P,i}})	
    \end{equation}

        \begin{equation}
	f_{R}(m_i) g_R(T) = R_{0,i} m_i^{a_R} e^{\frac{-E_{R,i}}{kT}} h(T_{pk_{R,i}}, 
	E_{D_{R,i}})	
    \end{equation}
}

   \end{columns}
  %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
 \block{How do species-level thermal performance curves (TPCs) give rise to an emergent thermal-dependence of the whole ecosystem?}{
     \centering
   \begin{minipage}[]{0.250\linewidth}
     \centering
     \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{IntraspPlots.pdf}
     \caption{\footnotesize Representative set of individual-level plot pairs for R (left) and NP (right). Each pair of R-NP corresponds to the same experiment and species. These species are associated to temperate regions.}
   \end{minipage}
	\hspace{.8cm}
	\begin{minipage}[]{0.20\linewidth}
               \centering
			\begin{itemize} \itemsep15pt \normalsize
				\item Are differences in species-level temperature-dependence of photosynthesis and respiration reflected in the ecosystem thermal response?. 
				\item Does the full unimodal thermal responses of metabolic rates matter for mapping individual TPCs to ecosystem-level fluxes?
. 
				\item Is simple scaling (as defined above) from species-level thermal responses sufficient to predict ecosystem-level responses?.
			\end{itemize}
		\end{minipage}
	\hspace{.5cm}
	\begin{minipage}[]{0.25\linewidth}
               \centering
	       \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{EcosystemPlots.pdf}
               \caption{\footnotesize Representative set of ecosystem flux responses to temperature for different sites from tropical and temperate regions. Y axis show respiration in log scale.}
		\end{minipage}
}
 


